{\fldrslt{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ul\cf1 The Winston-Salem Journal ran \u8220 Against Their Will,\u8221 }}}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2  a five-part series on North Carolina\u8217 s eugenics program. Immediately afterward, Gov. Mike Easley issued a public apology. In April 2003, the North Carolina Senate voted to overturn the sterilization law that had been on the books since 1919. In 2009, the state placed a historical marker in Raleigh to commemorate the 7,600 victims sterilized under the state\u8217 s eugenics laws between 1929 and 1974, and the media covered survivors\u8217  sharing memories of the trauma the surgery caused. In 2010, the North Carolina Justice for Sterilization Victims Foundation was started to find survivors; the following year, Gov. Bev Perdue appointed a task force to study a potential compensation package and its cost. Finally, in 2013, North Carolina\u8217 s Republican-controlled Legislature voted to spend $10 million to compensate the survivors of the state\u8217 s eugenics program.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 \u8220 There\u8217 s a huge movement all across the country to look at historical wrongs, including forced sterilization, and to consider what needs to be done now in order to redress them,\u8221  explains Margaret Burnham, founder and co-director of the Civil Rights and Restorative Justice Project at Northeastern University School of Law. \u8220 I think this is really the question of the 21st century.\u8221 }
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 Minnie Lee Relf never finished high school, dropping out in 11th grade. Keeping up with classwork was difficult for her, given the absence of formal learning in her early childhood and the limitations of her parents. \u8220 I was a slow reader in school,\u8221  she says now. \u8220 I can read, but I\u8217 m just slow. I was just slow.\u8221  She also recalls her classmates mocking her after learning of the case through media coverage. \u8220 People was just picking at me at school, always saying: \u8216 You can\u8217 t have no children. You can\u8217 t do this and you can\u8217 t ... ,\u8217 \u8221  she says, her voice trailing off. \u8220 It hurt me. I felt so sad.\u8221 }
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 Mary Alice was placed in McInnis, the special-needs school that Jessie Bly sought out for her. But she didn\u8217 t graduate, either. Their mother died in 1980, just as they reached adulthood, and their father in 2009. Katie, their older sister, lives in an apartment in the same complex. They are still bound tightly together, walking to the store for groceries, attending church, sitting side by side watching TV. \u8220 Some days I feel sad, but other times just tired,\u8221  says Minnie Lee, who explains that she and her sister struggle with hypertension and asthma, and that Mary Alice also suffers from seizures. \u8220 Not long ago, I was crying and felt like doing something to myself, like I wanted to go with my mom and dad,\u8221  Minnie Lee adds, looking over at her sister, who doesn\u8217 t seem to understand.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 Minnie Lee says she recalls the lawsuit; Levin, Dees and of course Miss Jessie Bly; the airplane trip to Washington and Senator Kennedy. But when I describe the impact of their case, how their story stopped the government from harming more girls and women like them, Minnie Lee looks confused. It is too much to comprehend. Mary Alice holds on to my arm and smiles.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 I met Katie in April. Now 66, she never finished high school. She and her husband, Michael, had one child, Jerome, who died shortly after he was born. Katie says she can barely remember anything about what happened to her and her sisters 50 years ago; she doesn\u8217 t understand why her family didn\u8217 t receive any compensation for what was done to them. \u8220 But I think about it every day, really,\u8221  she said.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 As I described the way her family\u8217 s case made history, she moved closer to listen. I then explained that apologies have been made to survivors in other places. An apology, she said, \u8220 would mean the world to us, and I would forgive them.\u8221  She looked away and began to weep.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 \u8220 Sterilization involves two forms of harm, the physical harm to one\u8217 s reproductive autonomy and the moral stigma associated with sterilization, including the suggestion that you are unworthy to reproduce, in the Relfs\u8217  case because they are Black women,\u8221  Burnham says. \u8220 These women bear a mark of being deemed less than a full person. That moral harm has to be addressed by an apology, and it must come from the state. But they are also owed material redress, some sort of financial repair. That\u8217 s what is clearly acknowledged in the Virginia, North Carolina and California initiatives: that practices of truth telling, repair and reparation must come into play when formal law fails.\u8221 }
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 Minnie Lee may not understand what the nation gained because of her case. But it is hauntingly, painfully clear that she understands what she and Mary Alice lost. When I visited, I saw that each woman slept with a brown baby doll, Mary Alice\u8217 s nestled in a tangle of sheets, Minnie Lee\u8217 s laid across her pillow. \u8220 I know I can\u8217 t have kids, and it gets to me sometimes,\u8221  Minnie Lee says. \u8220 Every time I see somebody like my cousin or my niece Debbie with their child, I think about it. Seeing these little pretty babies, I wish that was me.\u8221 }
